06118nam a22010215i 9780691216966DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020032357  a9780691216966  a(DE-B1597)576290  a(OCoLC)1257324871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aJQ1519.A5bD5297 2021 4aJQ1519.A5 7aPOL0050002bisacsh04a324.251/075qLOC1 aDickson, Bruce J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Party and the People :bChinese Politics in the 21st Century /cBruce J. Dickson. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b17 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tTHE PARTY AND THE PEOPLE -- tIntroduction -- t1 What Keeps the Party in Power -- t2 How Are Leaders Chosen -- t3 How Are Policies Made -- t4 Does China Have a Civil Society -- t5 Do Political Protests Threaten Political Stability -- t6 Why Does the Party Fear Religion -- t7 How Nationalistic Is China -- t8 Will China Become Democratic -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow the Chinese Communist Party maintains its power by both repressing and responding to its peopleSince 1949, the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) has maintained unrivalled control over the country, persisting even in the face of economic calamity, widespread social upheaval, and violence against its own people. Yet the party does not sustain dominance through repressive tactics alone—it pairs this with surprising responsiveness to the public. The Party and the People explores how this paradox has helped the CCP endure for decades, and how this balance has shifted increasingly toward repression under the rule of President Xi Jinping.Delving into the tenuous binary of repression and responsivity, Dickson illuminates numerous questions surrounding the CCP’s rule: How does it choose leaders and create policies? When does it allow protests? Will China become democratic? Dickson shows that the party’s dual approach lies at the core of its practices—repression when dealing with existential, political threats or challenges to its authority, and responsiveness when confronting localized economic or social unrest. The state answers favorably to the demands of protesters on certain issues, such as local environmental hazards and healthcare, but deals harshly with others, such as protests in Tibet, Xinjiang, or Hong Kong. With the CCP’s greater reliance on suppression since Xi Jinping’s rise to power in 2012, Dickson considers the ways that this tipping of the scales will influence China’s future.Bringing together a vast body of sources, The Party and the People sheds new light on how the relationship between the Chinese state and its citizens shapes governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical leadershipzChina. 0aPolitical partieszChinaxHistory. 0aPolitical planningzChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  aChina in the 21st Century.  aChinese nationalism.  aChinese politics.  aChinese religious believers.  aElizabeth Economy.  aHu Jintao.  aJeffrey Wasserstrom.  aJiang Zemin.  aJoseph Fewsmith.  aLeninism.  aMao Zedong.  aRethinking Chinese Politics.  aThe Third Revolution.  acivil society in China.  acompensation for seized property in China.  ademocratization in China.  alow wages in China.  anationalism in China.  apolicymaking in China.  apolitical protest in China.  areligion in China.  aresponsiveness without accountability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE C